my_map_theme <- function(){
  theme(panel.background=element_blank(),
        axis.text=element_blank(),
        axis.ticks=element_blank(),
        axis.title=element_blank())
}

Map Visualization Template

# Map of county boundaries in US
us_county <- counties_sf("laea") #load in county outline
## old-style crs object detected; please recreate object with a recent sf::st_crs()
outline_states <- usa_sf("laea") #load in state outline
## old-style crs object detected; please recreate object with a recent sf::st_crs()
# Get base form visualization
ggplot(us_county) + 
  geom_sf(size=0.25) + #sets county lines
  geom_sf(data = outline_states, alpha=0, size=0.5, color="black") + #thickens state lines
  my_map_theme() +
  labs(title = "This is a title",
       subtitle = "This is a subtitle") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size=15)) +
  theme(plot.subtitle = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

Data Wrangling

# First check for spelling differences and correct them to match 
# (City & Borough = Cty&Bor, Census Area = CA, Municipality = Muny)
# in us_county, check for blank lsad (District of Columbia, Carson City), City is lowercase city, Parish is in Louisiana, two Muny in Alaska
t(unique(us_county$lsad))
##      [,1]   [,2]   [,3] [,4] [,5] [,6]    [,7]    [,8]
## [1,] County Parish city      CA   Borough Cty&Bor Muny
## Levels:  Borough CA city County Cty&Bor Muny Parish
# Second separate or unite to match the titles of census areas
us_county_fix <- us_county %>%
  mutate(lsad = as.character(lsad))
us_county_fix$lsad <- replace(us_county_fix$lsad, us_county_fix$lsad == "city", "City") 
us_county_fix$lsad <- replace(us_county_fix$lsad, us_county_fix$lsad == "CA", "Census Area")
us_county_fix$lsad <- replace(us_county_fix$lsad, us_county_fix$lsad == "Cty&Bor", "City and Borough")
us_county_fix$lsad <- replace(us_county_fix$lsad, us_county_fix$lsad == "Muny", "Municipality")
us_county_unite <- us_county_fix %>%
  unite(col = "county", c("name","lsad"), sep = " ")
# In HAF, some of the City are city lowercase
HAF_fix <- HAF
HAF_fix$county <- gsub("city","City", HAF_fix$county)
# Petersburg Borough in HAF; Petersburg CA in us_county
us_county_unite$county <- gsub("Petersburg Census Area", "Petersburg Borough", us_county_unite$county)
# District of Columbia needs troubleshooting, likely due to the lsad being blank
us_county_unite$county <- gsub("District of Columbia ", "District of Columbia", us_county_unite$county)
# La Salle in Illinois is missing in HAF, LaSelle in us_county but spaced in HAF
us_county_unite$county <- gsub("LaSalle County", "La Salle County", us_county_unite$county)
# Carson City in Nevada, look into lsad being blank
us_county_unite$county <- gsub("Carson City ", "Carson City", us_county_unite$county)
# Dona Ana County in New Mexico missing in us_county because it has a tilde over the n there but not in HAF
us_county_unite$county <- gsub("Doa Ana County", "Dona Ana County", us_county_unite$county)


# Third join FIPS & Geometry by names
# HAF_test <- HAF_fix %>%
#   left_join(us_county_unite, by=c("county"="county", "st"="state"))
# Join into map data to preserve sf class on geometry
HAF_test <- us_county_unite %>%
  left_join(HAF_fix, by=c("county"="county", "state"="st"))

# Fix HAF characters into numeric, look into scientific numbers
HAF_test1 <- HAF_test %>%
  mutate(total_mortgages = as.numeric(total_mortgages),
         cost_burden = as.numeric(cost_burden),
         share_cost_burden = as.numeric(share_cost_burden),
         prop_cb_test = cost_burden/total_mortgages)

Visualizations

cb_cutpoints <- c(-0.001, 0.050, 0.100, 
                  0.200, 0.225, 0.250, 0.275,
                  0.300, 0.400, 0.500, 0.600, 0.700, 1.000)
cb_labels <- c("0.00% to 5.00%", "5.00% to 10.0%", "10.0% to 20.0%", 
               "20.0% to 22.5%", "22.5% to 25.0%", "25.0% to 27.5%", "27.5% to 30.0%", 
               "30.0% to 40.0%", "40.0% to 50.0%", "50.0% to 60.0%", "60.0% to 70.0%",
               "70.0% or more")
# Need to play around with color theory
# Google 'discrete color palette' hexcodes
# cb_colors <- c("#F8F359", "#F8E759", "#F8D959", 
#               "#F8C459", "#F8B459", "#F8A459", "#F89D59", 
#               "#F87559", "#F85959", "#D34444", "#B73D3D",
#               "#9E3636")
cb_colors <- c("#fff0a6", "#ffe871", "#ffdc39",
               "#ffb34e", "#e4a06a", "#de8565", "#de7565",
               "#de6565", "#be5151", "#9e3636", "#6f1e1e",
               "#390808")

HAF_viz_test <- HAF_test1 %>%
  mutate(cb_interval = cut(prop_cb_test, breaks = cb_cutpoints, labels = cb_labels))

Missing Data Shenanigans

HAF_test_NA <- HAF_viz_test %>%
  filter(is.na(prop_cb_test))

HAF_viz_NA <- HAF_viz_test %>%
  filter(is.na(cb_interval))

HAF_NA <- HAF %>%
  mutate(total_mortgages = as.numeric(total_mortgages),
         cost_burden = as.numeric(cost_burden),
         share_cost_burden = as.numeric(share_cost_burden),
         prop_cb_test = cost_burden/total_mortgages) %>%
  filter(is.na(prop_cb_test))

HAF_fix_NA <- HAF_fix %>%
  mutate(total_mortgages = as.numeric(total_mortgages),
         cost_burden = as.numeric(cost_burden),
         share_cost_burden = as.numeric(share_cost_burden),
         prop_cb_test = cost_burden/total_mortgages) %>%
  filter(is.na(prop_cb_test))

#   Shannon County in South Dakota, Wade Hampton Census Area in Alaska are missing in HAF, 3143 -> 3141
# Bedford City in Virginia is a special case since it has HAF but is not showing up in HAF_viz_test
# Bedford City and Bedford County in us_county, only Bedford County in HAF

# Look for the 3141, 3143, and 3144 difference

# Take the join data and filter it looking for NA in the columns that have HAF data from the us_county
# Removing counties that do not have HAF data, these will show up as white (blank) on the map
HAF_test3 <- us_county_unite %>%
  filter(county != "Shannon County" | state != "South Dakota", 
         county != "Wade Hampton Census Area" | state != "Alaska",
         county != "Bedford City") %>%
  left_join(HAF_fix, by=c("county"="county", "state"="st"))

HAF_test3 <- HAF_test3 %>%
  mutate(total_mortgages = as.numeric(total_mortgages),
         cost_burden = as.numeric(cost_burden),
         share_cost_burden = as.numeric(share_cost_burden),
         prop_cb_test = cost_burden/total_mortgages)

HAF_viz_test2 <- HAF_test3 %>%
  mutate(cb_interval = cut(prop_cb_test, breaks = cb_cutpoints, labels = cb_labels))

p <- ggplot(HAF_viz_test2) + 
  geom_sf(aes(fill=cb_interval), size=0.25, color="#2d2d2d") + #sets county lines
  scale_fill_manual("% Homeowners\nCost Burdened", values = cb_colors) +
  geom_sf(data = outline_states, alpha=0, size=0.5, color="black") + #thickens state lines
  my_map_theme() +
  labs(title = "Proportion of Cost Burdened Counties in 2019",
       subtitle = "Homeowners Spending 30% or More of Income on Outstanding Mortgages",
       caption = "*Bedford City, VA; Shannon County, SD; & Wade Census Area, AK are whited out due to not being included in Urban's data") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size=15)) +
  theme(plot.subtitle = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +

State & National Level

HAF_state <- HAF_write %>%
  mutate_at(27, ~replace_na(.,0)) %>%
  mutate(n_burdened_county = share_cost_burden*total_homeowners) %>%
  group_by(state) %>%
  mutate(n_burdened_state = sum(n_burdened_county)) %>%
  mutate(state_homeowners = sum(total_homeowners),
         state_share_burden = n_burdened_state/state_homeowners)
  
# histogram of share_burdened_states
HAF_state %>%
  select(state, state_share_burden) %>%
  distinct(state, state_share_burden) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = state_share_burden)) +
  geom_histogram(fill="#B5D77E", color="#8CA760") +
  labs(title = "# of States of Cost Burdened",
        y = "# of States",
        x = "Proportion of Cost Burdened Homeowners")
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

HAF_state %>%
  select(state, state_share_burden) %>%
  distinct(state, state_share_burden) %>%
  ggplot(aes(y = state_share_burden, x = state), width=.5) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", fill="#B5D77E", color="#8CA760") +
  coord_flip()

# national cost burden bars
HAF_nation <- HAF_state %>%
  select(state, state_share_burden, n_burdened_state, state_homeowners) %>%
  distinct(state, state_share_burden, n_burdened_state, state_homeowners)

n_b_nation <- sum(HAF_nation$n_burdened_state)

HAF_nat <- HAF_nation %>%
  summarize(share_burden_nation = n_burdened_state/n_b_nation,
            state_homeowners = state_homeowners)

HAF_nat %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = share_burden_nation, y = reorder(state,+share_burden_nation), share_burden_nation)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", width = 0.75)
